cated not far from the shore. The monsoon season, which runs from April to July, is the ideal time to visit. 2. Pawas Swarupanand Swami's tool samadhi at this place known as Pawas. The distance to Pawa from the town of Ratnagiri is 20 kilometers. Ramchandra, sometimes referred to as "Appa" or "Rambhau," was Swami's birth name. Swami, who committed self-immolation in Pawas and had lived here for 40 years before that, was born on December 15th, 1903. Born in Pawas to parents Vishnupant and Rakhmabai Godbole, The memorial contains a residence before Swamiji took self-immolation. It was on 15th August 1974 when he undertook self-immolation. In Pawas, the days of Swami's Samadhi and Guru Purnima are revered as important occasions. Currently, his home has been transformed into an ashram that serves as a place for followers to stay and eat. 3. Ganpatipule Beach On the Konkan coast in the Ratnagiri District of Maharashtra, southern India, the magnificent and breathtaking beach known as Ganpatipule Beach is located. This splendid beauty is also known for its 400-year-old Ganesha Temple, whose idol was allegedly made by itself and was rediscovered more than 1600 years ago. A variety of magnificent vegetation, including dense coconut palms and mangroves, can be found along Ganpatipule Beach's breathtaking and captivating coastline. Couples, families, and groups of friends can all enjoy a trip to this scenic area because of the peaceful surroundings and great escape from the boring and busy everyday lives of the inhabitants of Mumbai and the nearby districts. Since the location offers a variety of adventurous activities during certain months of the year, it is also a favorite destination for nature lovers and outdoor enthusiasts. To make the most out of your trip, you can enjoy numerous activities available at Ganpatipule Beach. Adventure sports, including paragliding, swimming, boat trips on motorboats, water scooters and pedal boats, camel rides, etc., are available for those seeking an adrenaline rush. Fortunately, the commercialization of Ganpatipule Beach hasn't had a major impact yet, and it still maintains its pristine state. This is the reason the beach still draws tens of thousands of visitors each year from throughout the nation who come in great numbers to the beach to take in some quiet time in the midst of nature. The Ganpatipule Beach is accessible all year round and has a tropical environment. beach lovers looking for adventure should go there between November and May as it mainly offers water activities during these months 4. Shri Devi Bhagwati Mandir Sri Devi Bhagwati Mandir, which is a portion of the enormous Ratnadurga fort, is one of India's oldest temples. Unique sculptures of gods like "Veer Vignesh" and "Ashtadash Bhuj" can be found inside the temple. You can also enjoy the beautiful view of the Arabian Sea while visiting the temple. The temple is located inside Ratnadurga Fort, formerly known as Bhagwati cha Killa (Bhagwati's fort). And this is how the temple came to be known as Sri Devi Bhagwati Mandir, as the temple is a section of Ratnadurga Fort. So, after a quick trip to the beach, one can tour Mirkarwada Jetty and the fort, which has the best views of the Arabian Sea. Hanuman's temple is also located inside the fort. The Navratri festival is the ideal time to visit the temple because, at this time, the temples are adorned with flowers and other decorations. During the Navratri celebration, the temple draws a large number of visitors; therefore, if you wish to avoid crowds, avoid visiting during this time. 5. Bhatye Beach A wonderful, long, and spotlessly clean beach, Bhatye Beach is perfect for a peaceful vacation. The abundant flat sea showers in Bhatye, a small town adjacent to Ratnagiri, are well-known. It is flat, straight, and clear for 1.5 kilometers of the beach's length. Bhatye Beach offers a view of the Ratnagiri lighthouse as well as the renowned Madavi beach in Ratnagiri city. One can gain a wonder