e Beach is perfect for a peaceful vacation. The abundant flat sea showers in Bhatye, a small town adjacent to Ratnagiri, are well-known. It is flat, straight, and clear for 1.5 kilometers of the beach's length. Bhatye Beach offers a view of the Ratnagiri lighthouse as well as the renowned Madavi beach in Ratnagiri city. One can gain a wonderful understanding of the many cultural traditions of Ganapatipule by visiting Bhatye Beach. You can take a morning stroll, relax, play football and beach volleyball in the sand, gather shells, or enjoy the magnificence of this beach. One must go to Kohinoor resort to view the dawn or sunset since it is a breathtaking sight that will leave you spellbound. The sand is as soft as velvet; it won't even stick to your body and can be effortlessly dusted off. You will feel as if you nearly have your own private island at the Bhatye beach because it is so tranquil and quiet. You may engage in a variety of interesting activities at Bhatye, thanks to its water sports facilities. This location will undoubtedly become a sports enthusiast's paradise thanks to the abundance of water-based activities and sports. There are caves that you can explore if you are not scared of the dark or caves that date back to ancient times. An important port may be found at Jaigadh Bandar, a well-known location. With your family members and friends, go fishing and have a boat ride. Keep your swimsuits, sunscreen, and other items close by. For a tour of the town, hire a guide. Any season of the year is suitable for visiting this beach. All twelve months of the year have quite pleasant weather here. 6. Gateway of Ratnagiri The Ratnagiri Gateway is a massive, towering building that overlooks the magnificent Arabian Sea. It is located in Ratnagiri on Mandavi Beach. It is a building in the Ratnagiri jetty area near Mandavi beach with a sloped roof. The beach is beautiful in itself. Pratinidhi Dhondu Bhaskar created the fortified building, which has numerous bastions, to protect Ratnagiri's coastline. The sea wind in this area is excellent, lulling you on a peaceful stroll as you take in the serene beach and the breathtaking horizon. 7. Velneshwar Velneshwar is a village south of Guhagar town in Maharashtra's Ratnagiri district. It is an amazing place to visit is Velneshwar, which is located north of the Shastri River. In addition to having a magnificent half-moon beach that is fresh, untouched, and perfect for swimming, Velneshwar is also known for its temple dedicated to Lord Shiva. When the Maha Shivratri Celebration is conducted in Velneshwar in honor of Lord Shiva in the month of March, the city enjoys a lot of attention. The Velneshwar Beach in Maharashtra is the right location for you if you're looking for a great water spot where you can enjoy the wonders of nature while swimming and sunbathing. The local fishing community makes up a substantial portion of the population. The nearby villagers are warm and welcoming. The most extensively used language is Marathi. Locals in this area are able to understand and speak both Hindi and English. Even if there aren't many marketplaces close by, for a more authentic experience, one could always visit Chitni Bazaar, Mahaveer Market, etc. The beach is highly appealing due to its smooth shoreline and vibrantly green coconut trees. For a quick journey into tranquility or a weekend family vacation, Velneshwar is the ideal destination. Velneshwar experiences tropical weather as it is a beach community. All year round, there is dampness. The months of the winter season, from November through February, are the finest times to visit Velneshwar. Summers can be extremely hot. Contrarily, the rain is captivating and delightful. 8. Velas Turtle Festival The Velas Turtle Festival is hosted on the Velas beach in Ratnagiri, which is 200 kilometers from Pune. One of the most well-known eco-festivals in India is the Velas Turtle Festival, which attracts volunteers, visitors, and travelers from all over the world. Some visitors come to help the small turtle hatchlings, others photograph the creatures as they make their way into the sea, and still others enjoy a relaxing eco-tourism experience on the shore. Travelers will remember the experience since it allows them to have fun while simultaneously giving back to the community and the environment. Unsurprisingly, the quantity of sea turtles has increased consistently since the festival's introduction, contributing to the economic improvement of the settlements along the Velas beach. For kids, participating in the turtle fest is ideal. This event is a pleasant break from the digital world of tablets and smartphones for the younger generation. For those who wish to witness the complete process of turtle breeding, hatching, and release into the sea, as well as take advantage of the ecotourism activities provided by the village community, a 2- to 3-day schedule is recommended. Visit the beach in the early morning or late at night to see the beautiful sight of newborn turtles making their way toward the water. The hours are 7 AM to 7:30 AM and 6 PM to 7 PM. If you are too excited about seeing the birth of a turtle, go for a walk on the beach around midnight to see the turtle's eggs hatch. 9. Ratnagiri Fort The Ratnagiri Fort, also known as Ratnadurg Fort or Bhagawati Fort, is situated 2 kilometres from Ratnagiri district of Maharashtra. In the Ratnagiri district, this fort is a significant fort. Due to the presence of the Bhagawati Temple within the fort, it is a major tourist destination. It was constructed during the Bahamian era. Adil Shah of Bijapur lost control of the fort to Maratha King Shivaji in 1670. King Shivaji had constructed defense towers at two strategic locations, one to the south as well as the other close to the former courthouse. Admiral Kanhoji Angre of the Marathas reinforced citadel defense between 1750 and 1755. During the Peshwa era, Dhondu Bhaskar Pratinidhi made a few modest repairs to the fort (1755-1818). The British eventually took control of the fort in 1818. In 1950, the Bhagavati temple underwent renovation. On one side of the fort, there is a lighthouse. There is a Bhagawati temple, a pond, and a well inside the fort. Below the fort, there is a cave. Rede Buruj is the bastion that is the strongest of all. 10. Patit Pawan Mandir In Ratnagiri, Maharashtra, India, there is a Hindu temple called Patit Pawan Mandir. On February 22, 1931, Vinayak Damodar Savarkar founded it, and Shriman Bhagojisheth Keer constructed it. The construction of the temple caused a stir in a time when untouchables were frequently dehumanized since it is a sanctuary in which even untouchables can worship their God as other people do. The Patit Pawan Mandir was used for parts in a Hindi movie directed by Sudhir Phadke about the life of Savarkar. Phadke actually finished singing and composing music for this movie as his final project. Next TopicTourist Places in Arunachal Pradesh ? prev next ? For Videos Join Our Youtube Channel: Join Now Feedback Send your Feedback to [email protected] Help Others, Please Share Learn Latest Tutorials Splunk SPSS Swagger Transact-SQL Tumblr ReactJS Regex Reinforcement Learning R Programming RxJS React Native Python Design Patterns Python Pillow Python Turtle Keras Preparation Aptitude Reasoning Verbal Ability Interview Questions Company Questions Trending Technologies Artificial Intelligence AWS Selenium Cloud Computing Hadoop ReactJS Data Science Angular 7 Blockchain Git Machine Learning DevOps B.Tech / MCA DBMS Data Structures DAA Operating System Computer Network Compiler Design Computer Organization Discrete Mathematics Ethical Hacking Computer Graphics Software Engineering Web Technology Cyber Security Automata C Programming C++ Java .Net Python Programs Control System Data Mining Data Warehouse Javatpoint Services JavaTpoint offers too many high quality services. Mail us on [email protected], to get more information about given service